mbed-os 5.8
C++11

I'm running into a hard fault issue.  Producing a crash dump suggests that the exception occurs at this line - https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-os/blob/master/events/equeue/equeue.c#L264

I've stared at the code awhile and am still not quite sure what's going on.  This question is not a request to solve this particular problem, but rather a general question for debugging `EventQueue`s

I have multiple event queues in my application so setting a breakpoint in the equeue code isn't going to help.  Is there any techniques that I can use to zero into a specific event queue dispatch run?  I suppose I could find a memory location for an element within the equeue struct to set a data watchpoint on.  If there's nicer techniques that you can share, that'd be awesome.

An approximation of the segment of code that I think is the location of the problem is

```
struct A {
  bool thing;
};

struct B {
  uint16_t thing;
};

struct User {
  EventQueue queue;

  void Run() { queue.dispatch_forever(); }

  template <typename Stuff>
  void CallDoStuff(const Stuff stuff) {
    queue.call(this, static_cast<void(User::*)(const Stuff)>(&User::DoStuff), stuff);
  }

  void DoStuff(const A a) { std::cout << "A!\n"; }
  void DoStuff(const B b) { std::cout << "B!\n"; }
};

User user;
Thread thread;

void main()
{
  thread.start(Callback<void()>(&user, User::Run));
  user.CallDoStuff(A{true});
  user.CallDoStuff(B{0xC0DE});
}
```

While I didnt try to ensure that this snippet compiles, my actual code does compile with a number of analogoues to the `DoStuff` overloads.  I'm wondering if the code got generated incorrectly, but looking at the elf file, I don't see anything jumping out.  The equeue could have overflowed, but that's not an abnormal condition, and I don't expect it to lead to a hard fault.

I did get a core dump using https://github.com/adamgreen/CrashCatcher but I'm embarrassingly new to post-mortem investigation with gdb and core dumps so I would like to be able to catch the issue in the act so to speak.

So, my question:  Is there any techniques or code changes I can do to:
- Examine the dispatch of a specific queue
- Examine the processing of a specific event (possibly periodic)

